# Exploratory Data Analysis

```{r}
# Missingness
colSums(is.na(flights_train[, c("dep_del15", "dep_time", "crs_dep_time")]))

flights_train |>
  summarise(across(everything(), ~mean(is.na(.)))) |>
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "variable", values_to = "pct_missing") |>
  filter(pct_missing > 0) |>
  arrange(desc(pct_missing)) |>
  print(n = 30)
```

Most of the missingness is in delay-reason columns (carrier delay, weather delay, etc.) that we can't use for prediction anyway. The main thing to check is whether any pre-departure features we actually plan to use have meaningful gaps.

```{r}
# Target distribution
flights_train |>
  count(dep_del15)

flights_train |>
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(dep_del15, labels = c("on time", "delayed")))) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Departure delay distribution", x = NULL, y = "count")
```

The classes are roughly 80/20 on-time vs. delayed. Since AUC is our evaluation metric this imbalance doesn't directly hurt us, but it's worth keeping in mind if we end up picking a classification threshold later.

```{r}
# Delay rate by carrier
flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(op_unique_carrier) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), n = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  arrange(desc(delay_rate)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(op_unique_carrier, delay_rate), y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by carrier", x = "carrier", y = "proportion delayed >= 15 min")
```

There's real variation across carriers, so this should be a useful predictor. Carriers with very few flights at PIT will have noisy estimates though — worth thinking about smoothing or grouping when we get to feature engineering.

```{r}
# Departure time distribution and delay rate by hour
flights_train |>
  ggplot(aes(x = dep_time)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 40) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of departure times", x = "departure time", y = "count")

flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15), !is.na(sched_dep_hour)) |>
  group_by(sched_dep_hour) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = sched_dep_hour, y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by scheduled departure hour", x = "hour", y = "proportion delayed >= 15 min")
```

Delays increase steadily through the day and peak in the evening. This is the delay cascade effect — a late plane from an earlier leg holds up the next departure. Early morning flights are the most on-time since planes are freshly repositioned overnight. `sched_dep_hour` is probably one of our strongest features.

```{r}
# Delay rate by carrier (stacked bar)
flights_train |>
  ggplot(aes(x = op_unique_carrier, fill = factor(dep_del15))) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Delay proportion by carrier", x = "carrier", y = "proportion", fill = "delayed")

# Delay rate by month
flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(month) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = delay_rate, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by month", x = "month", y = "proportion delayed >= 15 min")

# Delay rate by day of week
flights_train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(day_of_week) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week, y = delay_rate, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by day of week", x = NULL, y = "proportion delayed >= 15 min")
```

Delays are noticeably worse in summer (June–August) and December, which lines up with peak travel and weather. The day-of-week pattern is subtler — Thursdays and Fridays are slightly worse, Saturdays are the best day to fly. Both are worth including as features but probably won't carry as much weight as hour or carrier.

```{r}
# Top destinations
flights_train |>
  count(dest, sort = TRUE) |>
  slice_head(n = 15)
```

The most common routes are to major hubs (ORD, ATL, CLT, etc.), which makes sense for an airport PIT's size. Flights into busy hubs tend to be more delay-prone, so route-level delay rates could be a useful feature to engineer.
